  "prompt": "How often should employees get a performance review?",
  "response": "The frequency of performance reviews can vary depending on the company culture, industry, and specific organizational goals. However, common practices include:\n\n1. **Annual Reviews**: Many organizations conduct formal reviews once a year. This allows for a comprehensive evaluation of employee performance over a longer period.\n\n2. **Semi-Annual Reviews**: Some companies choose to conduct reviews twice a year to provide more frequent feedback and adjust goals as necessary.\n\n3. **Quarterly Reviews**: In fast-paced environments, quarterly reviews can help keep employees aligned with their objectives and provide ongoing feedback.\n\n4. **Continuous Feedback**: Instead of formal reviews, some organizations are moving towards a continuous feedback model, where managers provide regular, informal feedback throughout the year. This can be complemented by scheduled check-ins.\n\n5. **Project-Based Reviews**: In companies where work is organized around projects, some may conduct reviews at the end of each project to evaluate employee performance related to specific tasks.\n\nUltimately, the best approach depends on the needs of the organization and its employees. Regular feedback, regardless of the format, tends to promote employee development and engagement.",
